    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A declining balance loan, like a typical student loan, is calculated by applying interest to the remaining principal balance.  Even when you make a fixed payment, a significant portion of that payment goes towards covering the interest accrued that month, especially when the principal is high.  The interest is calculated *before* your payment is applied, and then the remaining amount reduces the principal. So, the interest is always calculated on the current, slightly smaller, balance from the previous month. This is why it can feel like your principal is moving slower than you expect.",
      "source": "target",
